04201nam a22004575i 9780226410357DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132005ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264103577 a10.7208/97802264103572doi  a(DE-B1597)524922  a(OCoLC)1045748674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aJordan, Mark D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlessing Same-Sex Unions :bThe Perils of Queer Romance and the Confusions of Christian Marriage /cMark D. Jordan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (268 p.) :b11 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION/ Uncivil Ceremonies -- tCHAPTER ONE. Some Boys’ Romance -- tCHAPTER TWO. A Proper Engagement -- tCHAPTER THREE. Your (?) Special Day -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Finding Some Marriage Theology— Before the Ceremony -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Wedding and Its Attendants -- tCHAPTER SIX. Afterward; or, Out of Bounds -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Ending in Time -- tEPILOGUE. A Comic Exhortation -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt most church weddings, the person presiding over the ritual is not a priest or a pastor, but the wedding planner, followed by the photographer, the florist, and the caterer. And in this day and age, more wedding theology is supplied by Modern Bride magazine or reality television than by any of the Christian treatises on holy matrimony. Indeed, church weddings have strayed long and far from distinctly Christian aspirations. The costumes and gestures might still be right, but the intentions are hardly religious. Why then, asks noted gay commentator Mark D. Jordan, are so many churches vehemently opposed to blessing same-sex unions? In this incisive work, Jordan shows how carefully selected ideals of Christian marriage have come to dominate recent debates over same-sex unions. Opponents of gay marriage, he reveals, too often confuse simplified ideals of matrimony with historical facts. They suppose, for instance, that there has been a stable Christian tradition of marriage across millennia, when in reality Christians have quarreled among themselves for centuries about even the most basic elements of marital theology, authorizing experiments like polygamy and divorce. Jordan also argues that no matter what the courts do, Christian churches will have to decide for themselves whether to bless same-sex unions. No civil compromise can settle the religious questions surrounding gay marriage. And queer Christians, he contends, will have to discover for themselves what they really want out of marriage. If they are not just after legal recognition as a couple or a place at the social table, do they really seek the blessing of God? Or just the garish melodrama of a white wedding? Posing trenchant questions such as these, Blessing Same-Sex Unions will be a must-read for both sides of the debate over gay marriage in America today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226410357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226410357.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles